  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence uses commas correctly in a list?',['She bought apples, oranges, bananas, and mangoes.','She bought apples oranges bananas and mangoes.','She bought apples, oranges, bananas and, mangoes.','She bought apples oranges, bananas, and mangoes.'],'She bought apples, oranges, bananas, and mangoes.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence uses a comma correctly after an introductory clause?',['After the rain had stopped, we continued our journey.','After the rain had stopped we continued our journey.','After, the rain had stopped we continued.','After the rain had stopped; we continued.'],'After the rain had stopped, we continued our journey.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence correctly uses a semicolon?',['She was tired; nevertheless, she continued to work.','She was tired; but she continued to work.','She was tired; and she continued to work.','She was tired; to continue working.'],'She was tired; nevertheless, she continued to work.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','When should a semicolon be used?',['To connect two closely related independent clauses','To separate items in a simple list','After an introductory word only','Before a conjunction like "and"'],'To connect two closely related independent clauses',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence correctly sets off a non-essential clause with commas?',['The teacher, who had been there for twenty years, retired last June.','The teacher who had been there for twenty years retired last June.','The teacher who had been there, for twenty years, retired last June.','The teacher, who had been there for twenty years retired last June.'],'The teacher, who had been there for twenty years, retired last June.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence correctly uses a semicolon between two independent clauses?',['The examination was difficult; many students found it challenging.','The examination was difficult; but many students found it challenging.','The examination was difficult; to make students struggle.','The examination; was difficult and many students found it challenging.'],'The examination was difficult; many students found it challenging.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence has a comma error?',['She ate rice, chicken, and vegetables for lunch.','Although she was tired she completed the assignment.','After the bell rang, the students left.','He was late, but he still caught the bus.'],'Although she was tired she completed the assignment.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which is the correct use of a comma before a coordinating conjunction?',['He studied hard, but he still failed the test.','He studied hard but, he still failed.','He studied hard but he still failed, the test.','He, studied hard but he still failed.'],'He studied hard, but he still failed the test.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence uses a semicolon incorrectly?',['She likes reading; he prefers playing football.','I enjoy painting; my brother enjoys sculpture.','The exam is tomorrow; I should study tonight.','He ran fast; but still missed the bus.'],'He ran fast; but still missed the bus.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,1,'grammar','Which sentence correctly uses commas with a non-essential phrase?',['Lagos, Nigeria\'s largest city, is home to over 20 million people.','Lagos Nigeria\'s largest city is home to over 20 million people.','Lagos, Nigeria\'s largest city is home to over 20 million people.','Lagos Nigeria\'s largest city, is home to over 20 million people.'],'Lagos, Nigeria\'s largest city, is home to over 20 million people.',term:2),

  // Set 2
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Edit: "She baked cookies cakes and pies for the school fair."',['She baked cookies, cakes, and pies for the school fair.','She baked cookies, cakes and pies, for the school fair.','She baked; cookies, cakes, and pies.','She baked cookies cakes, and pies.'],'She baked cookies, cakes, and pies for the school fair.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Edit: "Because she worked hard she earned the highest grade."',['Because she worked hard, she earned the highest grade.','Because she worked hard; she earned the highest grade.','Because she worked hard she earned, the highest grade.','Because, she worked hard she earned the highest grade.'],'Because she worked hard, she earned the highest grade.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Which version correctly uses a semicolon?',['The library closes at six; students must leave by then.','The library closes at six; and students must leave by then.','The library closes; at six students must leave.','The library; closes at six students must leave.'],'The library closes at six; students must leave by then.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Which version correctly places a comma after an introductory phrase?',['In the morning, the students gathered in the hall.','In the morning the students, gathered in the hall.','In the morning the students gathered, in the hall.','In the morning; the students gathered.'],'In the morning, the students gathered in the hall.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Which correctly sets off a non-essential clause?',['My brother, who lives in Abuja, is a doctor.','My brother who lives in Abuja, is a doctor.','My brother, who lives in Abuja is a doctor.','My brother who lives, in Abuja, is a doctor.'],'My brother, who lives in Abuja, is a doctor.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','A semicolon can replace which punctuation when clauses are closely related?',['A full stop','A comma','An apostrophe','A colon before a list'],'A full stop',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Which sentence uses all punctuation correctly?',['She is intelligent, hardworking, and determined; she will certainly succeed.','She is intelligent hardworking and determined, she will certainly succeed.','She is intelligent, hardworking, and determined, she will certainly succeed.','She is intelligent; hardworking, and determined; she will succeed.'],'She is intelligent, hardworking, and determined; she will certainly succeed.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Which sentence has a comma splice?',['The sun set, the stars appeared.','The sun set; the stars appeared.','The sun set, and the stars appeared.','After the sun set, the stars appeared.'],'The sun set, the stars appeared.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Edit: "He was nervous however he performed brilliantly."',['He was nervous; however, he performed brilliantly.','He was nervous, however he performed brilliantly.','He was nervous however; he performed brilliantly.','He was nervous however, he performed brilliantly.'],'He was nervous; however, he performed brilliantly.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,2,'grammar','Which transition word requires a semicolon before it when connecting two independent clauses?',['therefore','because','although','while'],'therefore',term:2),

  // Set 3 — comprehension: punctuation passage
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'comprehension','PASSAGE — Punctuation Rules: The comma is one of the most versatile punctuation marks in English. It separates items in a list, follows introductory clauses, and sets off non-essential information. The semicolon connects two closely related independent clauses that could each stand alone (e.g. "The storm was approaching; we sought shelter immediately"). A common error is the comma splice — using only a comma to join two independent clauses, which is incorrect.\n\nQ: According to the passage, what are THREE uses of the comma?',['Separating list items, following introductory clauses, and setting off non-essential information','Connecting independent clauses, separating adjectives, and ending sentences','Replacing semicolons, ending quotations, and forming questions','Listing verbs, joining adjectives, and indicating pauses'],'Separating list items, following introductory clauses, and setting off non-essential information',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'comprehension','Refer to the passage above (punctuation).\n\nQ: When is a semicolon used?',['To connect two closely related independent clauses that could each stand alone','To separate items in a list','After an introductory clause only','Before a coordinating conjunction'],'To connect two closely related independent clauses that could each stand alone',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'comprehension','Refer to the passage above (punctuation).\n\nQ: What is a "comma splice"?',['Using only a comma to join two independent clauses — which is incorrect','Using a semicolon instead of a comma','Forgetting a comma in a list','Using a comma before "and"'],'Using only a comma to join two independent clauses — which is incorrect',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'comprehension','Refer to the passage above (punctuation).\n\nQ: Could "The storm was approaching" and "we sought shelter immediately" each stand alone?',['Yes — both are complete sentences','No — neither clause can stand alone','Only the second clause can stand alone','Only the first clause can stand alone'],'Yes — both are complete sentences',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'comprehension','Refer to the passage above (punctuation).\n\nQ: What does the passage call "using only a comma to join two independent clauses"?',['A comma splice — an error','A semicolon construction','A non-essential clause','An introductory phrase'],'A comma splice — an error',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'grammar','Identify the comma splice:',['The match was exciting, we all cheered loudly.','The match was exciting; we all cheered loudly.','The match was exciting, and we all cheered loudly.','Although the match was exciting, we remained calm.'],'The match was exciting, we all cheered loudly.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'grammar','Which sentence is correctly punctuated throughout?',['Kano, the ancient northern city, is famous for its markets, leather goods, and rich history.','Kano the ancient northern city, is famous for its markets leather goods and rich history.','Kano, the ancient northern city is famous for its markets, leather goods, and rich history.','Kano, the ancient northern city, is famous for its markets; leather goods; and rich history.'],'Kano, the ancient northern city, is famous for its markets, leather goods, and rich history.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'grammar','Which pair of sentences should be joined with a semicolon?',['She finished early. / She used the time to review her answers.','She finished early and reviewed her answers.','She finished early, and she reviewed her answers.','She finished early because she reviewed her answers.'],'She finished early. / She used the time to review her answers.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'grammar','Edit: "It was cold outside, we decided to stay indoors."',['It was cold outside; we decided to stay indoors. OR It was cold outside, and we decided to stay indoors.','It was cold outside, so; we decided to stay indoors.','It was cold, outside we decided to stay indoors.','It was cold outside we decided; to stay indoors.'],'It was cold outside; we decided to stay indoors. OR It was cold outside, and we decided to stay indoors.',term:2),
  _qu2('upper','suffix',11,3,'grammar','Which is correctly punctuated with "however" as a conjunctive adverb?',['She was exhausted; however, she kept running.','She was exhausted, however; she kept running.','She was exhausted; however she kept running.','She was exhausted, however, she kept running.'],'She was exhausted; however, she kept running.',term:2),

